{"id":"2207.14283","submitter":"Charles Burnette Jr","authors":"Charles Burnette","title":"On power maps over weakly periodic rings","comments":"14 pages, 2 tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA math.NT","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  A ring $R$ is called weakly periodic if every $x \\in R$ can be written in the\nform $x = a + b,$ where $a$ is nilpotent and $b^m = b$ for some integer $m >\n1.$ The aim of this note is to consider when a nonzero nilpotent element $r$ is\nthe period of some power map $f(x) = x^n,$ in the sense that $f(x + r) = f(x)$\nfor all $x \\in R,$ and how this relates to the structure of weakly periodic\nrings.\n  In particular, we provide a new proof of the fact that weakly periodic rings\nwith central and torsion nilpotent elements are periodic commutative torsion\nrings. We also prove that $x^n$ is periodic over such rings whenever $n$ is not\ncoprime with each of the additive orders of the nilpotent elements. These are\nin fact the only periodic power maps over finite commutative rings with unity.\nFinally, we describe and enumerate the distinct power maps over Corbas $(p, k,\n\\phi)$-rings, Galois rings, $\\mathbb{Z}/n\\mathbb{Z},$ and matrix rings over\nfinite fields.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Jul 2022 17:59:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-07-29"}
