{"id":"2207.14307","submitter":"Xander Faber","authors":"Xander Faber, Jon Grantham, Everett W. Howe","title":"On the Maximum Gonality of a Curve over a Finite Field","comments":"23 pages; supporting code and scripts can be found at\n  https://github.com/RationalPoint/excessive","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The gonality of a smooth geometrically connected curve over a field $k$ is\nthe smallest degree of a nonconstant $k$-morphism from the curve to the\nprojective line. In general, the gonality of a curve of genus $g \\ge 2$ is at\nmost $2g - 2$. Over finite fields, a result of F.K. Schmidt from the 1930s can\nbe used to prove that the gonality is at most $g+1$. Via a mixture of geometry\nand computation, we improve this bound: for a curve of genus $g \\ge 5$ over a\nfinite field, the gonality is at most $g$. For genus $g = 3$ and $g = 4$, the\nsame result holds with exactly $217$ exceptions: There are two curves of genus\n$4$ and gonality $5$, and $215$ curves of genus $3$ and gonality $4$. The\ngenus-$4$ examples were found in other papers, and we reproduce their equations\nhere; in supplementary material, we provide equations for the genus-$3$\nexamples.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 28 Jul 2022 18:00:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-01"}
